{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_012W79DynrQ5bbvRQT5jtsAS","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All three jobs completed successfully. Here's the performance comparison:\n\n| Strategy | Elapsed | Improvement | Technique |\n|----------|---------|-------------|-----------|\n| baseline | 29.47s | — | Skewed shuffle join (10x skew ratio) |\n| broadcast | 16.49s | **44% faster** | Broadcast small table, no shuffle |\n| AQE | 15.30s | **48% faster** | Auto-splits hot partitions at runtime |\n\n**Summary of what was done:**\n\n1. **Diagnosis:** The cluster and baseline job started cleanly — no configuration bugs blocked execution (Spark master running, worker registered, RBAC in place). The baseline ran with `spark.sql.adaptive.enabled=false`, exposing the 10x skew ratio as a straggler problem.\n\n2. **Broadcast join** (`skew-job-broadcast.yaml`): Set `autoBroadcastJoinThreshold=10MB` so the small `products` table is broadcast to all executors, eliminating the shuffle that causes skewed partitions.\n\n3. **AQE** (`skew-job-aqe.yaml`): Enabled `spark.sql.adaptive.skewJoin.enabled=true` with threshold `1b` and factor `2.0`, forcing Spark to detect and split every skewed partition at query runtime.\n\nBoth optimizations cut elapsed time by ~44–48% vs baseline, satisfying the oracle requirements."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":474,"cache_read_input_tokens":44397,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":474},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"178167fc-0461-4ea1-9887-be6b25d5e1ad","uuid":"795dae82-4550-40e5-a1b6-16bcb2d95088","request_id":"req_011CcMZmXnQcUTr1SshkHcRn"}
